(LR), as well as the MK 68 Clandestine Delivered Mine (CDM) program and its associated mine launching system.

Project 0605: Long Range Aerial Delivery Maritime Mine (LRADMM) is a series of development, integration, and test efforts for the QS Family of Mines that support
greater precision mine placement, increased warhead lethality, new mine component development, expanded launch-platform integration and increasingly greater stand-
off delivery ranges enabled by the use of extended-range wing kits and long-range powered delivery vehicles.

Project 2993: Funds are associated with sensor upgrades to allow the Hammerhead system to prosecute additional targets.

Project 9999: FY25 Congressional Add funds effort to demonstrate an air-delivered, long-range, powered, maritime mine solution for the Quickstrike Family of Mines.

The Mines Improvement PE provides resources to develop naval mine systems used to establish and maintain control of essential sea areas. Naval mines are used to
deny sea areas or inflict damage on adversary shipping to hinder, disrupt, and deny adversary operations. Naval mining is employed to reduce the adversary's threat
to friendly forces and preserve access. Mining complements and performs an essential part of other warfare areas; particularly strike, anti-submarine, and anti-surface
warfare. Resources are utilized for developing and deploying improvements to the portfolio of naval mines.

The FY 2026 spend plan for Mine Development includes $0.130M of discretionary and $178.326M of mandatory for a total of $178.456M. Mandatory funding supported
QS-ER, CDM, QS MOD 3 development efforts.
