A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Naval mines are used to deter or control adversary movements, including surface ships and submarines. Funding supports the capability to maintain effectiveness of
mines facing new threat targets with increasing emphasis on major regional conflicts and near peer threats. The four major project areas are:

1) Quickstrike (QS) MOD 3: MOD 3 efforts improves effectiveness of existing mines against modern threats by using the programmable MK71 Target Detection Device
(TDD). Through modeling and analysis, the TDD's target detections and responses are improved with optimized mine settings and firing algorithms. The development of
the MK71 TDD supports minefield planning software improvements include new targeting algorithms, mine settings, and corresponding damage data for weapon /target
pairs.
2) Quickstrike Extended Range (QS-ER): A guidance kit and a wing assembly is added to the (QS Family of Mine)s to enable precision placement, increased delivery
ranges and reduced risk to the delivery platform. This aerial delivery development effort addresses capabilities required by a Joint Emergent Operational Needs
Statement (JEONS).
3) Quickstrike Long Range (QS-LR): A powered delivery vehicle is added to the QS Family of Mines to increase the delivery range beyond that of QS-ER and further
reduce the risk to the delivery platform. This aerial delivery development effort addresses capabilities required by a Joint Emergent Operational Needs Statement
(JEONS).

4) Clandestine Delivered Mine: Clandestine Delivered Mine MK68 (CDM MOD 0) provides a required capability by converting legacy mining systems for delivery by
Extra Large Unmanned Undersea Vehicles (XLUUV) and/or alternate platform in support of JEONS. This capability allows access to contested environments and
reduces risk by using unmanned platforms. Upgrades to CDM incorporate the programmable MK71 TDD and adds iterative command and control enhancements (MODs
1 and 2) through future upgrades for increased operational flexibility and safety for emplaced minefields. Additional efforts include transitioning an explosive section
design into the CDM program that is in development under the Compact Encapsulated Effector (C-ENCAP) effort that is managed by the Office of Naval Research
(ONR). In FY27 a mine launching system will begin development.

