A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Rolling Airframe Missile (RAM) program is an international cooperative program with the government of the Federal Republic of Germany. The purpose of this
program is to develop, test, and field a surface-to-air self-defense system consisting of both a missile and launcher. The latest fielded variant, the RAM Block 2B,
defends against highly maneuverable Anti-Ship Missile (ASM) threats and emerging complex raid attacks utilizing an advanced seeker and missile-to-missile link while
retaining all the proven capabilities of previous RAM variants (Block 0/1/1A/2/2A); accurate terminal guidance, proven lethality, and post-launch fire and forget capability.

 FY 2027 through FY 2031 efforts are as follows: Complete integration of the latest RAM Guided Missile Weapon System (GMWS) into the Ship Self-Defense System
 (SSDS) Baseline (BL) 12 and Aegis Combat System. This will enable the fleet to deploy the full capability of the RAM Block 2B missile which entered production in
 FY 2023. Continue the RAM "Performance Lab" which identifies improvements for incorporation through real-world events, trade studies, modelling and simulation,
 experiments, and test firings. Continue the RAM Software Factory to provide end users with rapid missile software updates to address emerging threats. Develop the
 Ship to Missile Uplink/Downlink (Stowed Kill Improvement Project (SKIP)). SKIP will utilize missile uplinks to provide the missile with continuous data from the combat
 system to improve mid-course and increase the probability of kill against complex raids. SKIP downlink will provide data back to the combat system to improve kill
 assessment fidelity. These system performance and efficiency improvements will be leveraged to decrease the required missiles per threat therefore increasing stowed
 kills per launcher.

