A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Evolved SEASPARROW Missile (ESSM) Blk 1 and Blk 2 is a NATO cooperative program, including the U.S., to defend against fast, low-altitude Anti-Ship Cruise
Missiles (ASCMs). It enhances shipboard firepower by enabling four ESSMs to be launched from a single MK 41 Vertical Launch System (VLS) cell on DDG and CG.

 This project supports eight primary efforts:

 1. ESSM Systems Integration and Test: ESSM Blk 2 is undergoing Initial Operational Test & Evaluation (IOT&E) Phase 2 and integration on platforms like CVN 79 and
 LHA 8. It supports AEGIS and SSDS baseline testing and flight trials, using missile simulators and flight test rounds.

 2. NATO SEASPARROW Technical Direction Agent (TDA): Provides systems engineering for the MK 57 NATO SEASPARROW System, including the MK 9 Tracker and
 MK 29 Launcher. These analyses and studies have been completed; future submissions will not include these efforts as they have transitioned to OPN.

 3. ESSM Technology Roadmap Analysis & Prototyping support: Ongoing studies seek performance and producibility improvements for ESSM Blk 2 and future variants,
 exploring new tech and manufacturing methods to support evolving threats. Efforts will align closely to the developing requirements of the Navy Modular Missile.

 4. Other Development (Blk 2 Obsolescence and Redesign, Combat System Test Bed (CSTB) and Models: Integrates ESSM Tactical Simulations into the CSTB/ETB to
 assess self-defense capabilities. Includes redesign studies to address aging components and support future missile models. This line will evolve into future M&S/MBSE
 tools in support of the next generation missile.

 5. Evolved SEASPARROW Missile (ESSM) Blk 2 Software Upgrades: Updates driven by IOT&E findings, flight tests, and system changes will enhance ESSM Blk 2
 capability. This line has completed its RDTE phase and will be incorporated in OMN budget.

 6. C-Band Telemetry Upgrade: To support testing with multiple simultaneous missile flights, telemetry has shifted from S-band to C-band. The analyses and studies have
 been completed. Future submissions will not include these efforts. C-band telemeters in production and have replaced S-band type on production line.

 7. NATO SEASPARROW Tracker-Illuminator System (TIS) Development: Efforts for previous OT-234 studies and analyses have been completed. Efforts to upgrade
 are required to existing ship's infrastructure to provide Semi-Active (SAX) illumination source that improves ESSM Blk 2 performance. The upgraded MK TIS will
 improve Combat System probability of kill against many targets. The receiver and tracking elements have reached the limits of their ability to support current system
 requirements. This effort will qualify, test, and integrate modernized equipment and components as part of the evolved MK 9 TIS.


