INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0605220N$$, 2027, $$The Ship-to-Shore Connector (SSC), also known as the LCAC 100 class, is the direct, one-for-one replacement for the U.S. Navy's aging fleet of Landing Craft, Air
Cushion (LCAC) vehicles, which have an average age of 32 years and began reaching their extended service life in 2015. It will replace legacy LCAC capacity in
enabling the rapid response of the Amphibious Ready Group and Marine Expeditionary Unit operations. The SSC is an aluminum air-cushion vehicle (hovercraft)
designed to enhance the Navy and Marine Corps' capability to execute a broad spectrum of missions from humanitarian assistance to major combat. Its primary role is
to efficiently transport weapon systems, equipment, cargo, and personnel of the Marine Air/Ground Task Force. As a high-speed, amphibious craft, it projects power by
being fully compatible with all allied amphibious ships, while performing assaults and operational maneuvers from ship to shore and across the beach.

 This PE directly funds and supports the detail design, development, construction, issue resolution, certification, integration and testing of the Ship to Shore Connector
 (SSC). The lead craft (Craft 100) will be maintained as a test and training platform throughout its life cycle.

 The FY 2026 spend plan for SSC included $7,267 thousand of discretionary and $1,688 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $8,955 thousand. The
 mandatory funding funds the operations and maintenance of Craft 100, the test and training craft.

 Note: This effort was previously funded under PE 0604567N under projects 3133 and 3137 (FY 2014 and prior).
Development & Demonstration (SDD)$$, $$This project provides funding for Ship to Shore Connector class propeller qualification and production including various improvement efforts to establish CONUS
propeller production stability. The SSC is an aluminum air-cushion vehicle (hovercraft) designed to enhance the Navy and Marine Corps' capability to execute a broad
spectrum of missions from humanitarian assistance to major combat. Its primary role is to efficiently transport weapon systems, equipment, cargo, and personnel of the
Marine Air/Ground Task Force. As a high-speed, amphibious craft, it projects power by being fully compatible with all allied amphibious ships, while performing assaults
and operational maneuvers from ship to shore and across the beach.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                    FY 2025 FY 2026
Congressional Add: Naval Hovercraft Composite System                                                                      0.000   8.681
FY 2025 Accomplishments: N/A
FY 2026 Plans: Developmental efforts related to technical solutions for SSC propellers and composites
