acoustic augmentation systems for the U.S. Navy submarines. The SAWS Development Program is comprised of Submarine Torpedo Defensive Systems (SubTDS)
(MK 5 and MK 6), Submarine Tethered Expendable Buoy (STEB), Compact Rapid Attack Weapon (CRAW), Non-Traditional Acoustic Communications (NTAC), and
Submarine Launched Unmanned Aerial System (SLUAS).

The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Submarine Acoustic Warfare Development Program includes $47,701 thousand of discretionary and $63,700 thousand of
mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $111,401 thousand.

Project 1265 Sub Defensive Warfare

The Submarine Torpedo Defense System (SubTDS) program delivers advanced acoustic countermeasures to protect submarines against enemy torpedo threats
through a phased development approach.

ADC MK5: The primary focus is delivering full Internal Countermeasure Launcher (ICL) functionality fleet-wide through the Acoustic Device Countermeasure (ADC)
MK5. This developmental contract, awarded in September 2018, is currently in Engineering and Manufacturing Development (E&MD) phase. The development follows
a phased approach, beginning with Engineering Development Models (EDMs) before transitioning to fully functional test units for Developmental Testing (DT) and
Operational Testing (OT). Upon successful completion of DT and OT, the program will proceed to Low-Rate Initial Production (LRIP). The ADC MK5 incorporates new
adaptive technologies in a three-inch diameter form factor and will evolve through software/hardware upgrades, improved mobility, combat control system integration via
ICL, and enhanced functionality to counter advancing torpedo threats.

ADC MK6: Development of a six-inch acoustic countermeasure for External Countermeasure Launcher (ECL) deployment. The ADC MK6 will build upon the
technological advancements developed by the ADC MK5 program. The MK6 Other Transaction Agreement (OTA) initiated development and prototyping efforts
continuing through the Future Years Defense Program (FYDP).
(TEMPALT).

Project 1267 CRAW

The FY 2027 budget supports development and delivery of a new very-lightweight torpedo to the submarine Force via the CRAW Technology Insertion 1 (TI-1) and
Technology Insertion 2 (TI-2) acquisition programs. CRAW provides enhanced Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW) and Anti-Torpedo Torpedo (ATT) mission capabilities.
The CRAW TI-1 program rapidly delivers fieldable prototypes by modifying existing legacy hardware. This legacy hardware is no longer manufacturable, so the CRAW
TI-2 program addresses obsolescence issues to establish an updated design baseline that is manufacturable by industry.

Two incremental hardware Technology Insertions, TI-1 and TI-2, will be used to deliver developmental prototypes to support Engineering, Development, and Operational
Testing. The ASW and ATT capabilities will be delivered via two Advanced Processor Build (APB) software spirals. The ASW capability will be part of APB-1 and
the ATT capability will be included in APB-2. The CRAW TI-1 effort is being executed as a Middle Tier of Acquisition (MTA) effort and will rapidly develop fieldable
prototypes to demonstrate the new very-lightweight torpedo ASW capabilities in an operational environment. Due to obsolescence there is a limited inventory of TI-1
systems. The TI-2 effort will update the TI-1 baseline to address obsolescence and improve producibility and supportability to enable production of additional inventory
so that the CRAW capability can be fielded broadly across the submarine force. The TI-2 program is a post-Milestone B (MS-B) ACAT III Major Capability Acquisition
Program. The TI-2 program is being phased with the TI-1 effort so that the TI-2 program can fully leverage the TI-1 prototypes as proof of design hardware. This will
reduce overall cost of the TI-2 program as the TI-2 program will move into development of proof of manufacturing prototypes to support Development Testing. Low-Rate
Initial Production (LRIP) units to support Operational Testing will also be delivered as part of TI-2. The CRAW program also includes development of submarine launcher
system modifications to allow for launch capabilities from vertical and horizontal launch tubes. This will include the development of the Revolver horizontal launcher
system that enables launch of multiple very- lightweight torpedoes from standard submarine torpedo tubes.

The TI-1 program includes safety qualification testing, submarine integration, operational testing via Quick Reaction Assessment (QRA), and delivery of TI-1 Warshot
prototypes. The FY27 budget also supports delivery of the initial TI-2 prototypes, TI-2 qualification testing, planning, development of the Anti-Torpedo Torpedo (ATT)
software, development of modeling and simulation capabilities, and ordering material for Proof of Design units to support in-water engineering testing.

Project 1268 NTAC

NTAC provides advanced undersea acoustic communications across multiple platforms within the Navy. This program builds upon the baseline NTAC software
capability and integrates the software components into existing hardware to expand the effectiveness and reliability of the capability. Additional details are available at
the classified level.

SLUAS extends the sensor range of the submarine. SLUAS sub-systems include the unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV), UAV encapsulating canister, UAV command and
control capabilities, and onboard stowage. Funding supports development and testing of capability improvements that will be part of the next variant AUR.
Systems Development$$, $$Revolver delivers hardware and middleware to enable smaller payloads to be launched from a VIRGINIA Class Torpedo Tubes. CRAW will be the first payload
integrated for use with the Revolver production baseline. While CRAW will be the initial payload integrated with Revolver, additional payloads that meet interface
requirements can be integrated.

Project C311: Congressional Add in FY 2025 ($3.858M) - Accelerate revolver integration

