D. Acquisition Strategy
The Service Life Assessment Program (SLAP) program employs sole source contracts with Boeing, the aircraft prime manufacturer. SLAP further decomposes program
of record goals into smaller discrete steps, developing requirements to extend flight hours (FH) from 6,000 to 10,000. These efforts will provide the raw engineering data
to develop aircraft modifications to extend total aircraft landings, Cat/Traps, and FH. The F/A-18 and EA-18G SLAP Program consists of two major engineering efforts:
the aircraft structural assessment and the aircraft subsystems assessment. Both efforts are broken into multiple phases which develop tools and models, evaluate
current aircraft usage and develop concepts to extend aircraft life to meet CNO inventory objectives. The program will utilize structural fatigue testing data and actual
fleet usage data with the expectation of extending the service life of the F/A-18 aircraft. Conducting both F/A-18E/F and EA-18G SLAP to study the aircraft lifetime will
provide a better estimate of aircraft service life and a follow on Service Life Extension Program (SLEP).




